  "prompt": "What is the relation between frequency and time period?",
  "response": "Frequency and time period are inversely related to each other. Frequency is defined as the number of cycles or oscillations per unit time, usually measured in Hertz (Hz), whereas the time period is the duration of time it takes to complete one cycle or oscillation, typically measured in seconds (s).\n\nMathematically, the relationship between frequency (f) and time period (T) can be expressed as:\n\n\\[ f = \\frac{1}{T} \\]\n\nor equivalently,\n\n\\[ T = \\frac{1}{f} \\]\n\nThis means that if the frequency increases, the time period decreases, and vice versa. For example, if a wave has a frequency of 2 Hz, its time period would be:\n\n\\[ T = \\frac{1}{2} = 0.5 \\text{ seconds} \\]\n\nSimilarly, if the time period of a wave is 0.25 seconds, its frequency would be:\n\n\\[ f = \\frac{1}{0.25} = 4 \\text{ Hz} \\]\n\nThis inverse relationship is fundamental in the study of oscillatory and wave phenomena in physics.",
